  "prompt": "If nails and hair are basically dead cells, how come they grow?",
  "response": "Great question! While nails and hair are primarily composed of dead cells, their growth occurs at the base, where living cells are actively dividing and producing new material.\n\n1. **Hair Growth**: Hair grows from hair follicles, which are located in the dermis (the deeper layer of your skin). At the base of each follicle is the hair bulb, where living cells divide and produce a protein called keratin. As these cells multiply, they push older cells upward. These older cells die, harden, and form the hair shaft, which is the part of the hair you see above the skin. So, the growth is driven by the living cells at the follicle's base, not the dead cells of the hair shaft.\n\n2. **Nail Growth**: Nails grow from the nail matrix, a structure located under the skin at the base of your nails. The matrix contains living cells that divide and produce keratin, the protein that makes up the nail plate. As new cells are produced, older cells are pushed forward, harden, and form the visible part of the nail. The pinkish part of the nail (the lunula) is the visible part of the matrix, and growth occurs here.\n\nIn both cases, the visible parts of nails and hair are technically \"dead,\" but their growth is fueled by the activity of living cells at their roots. The dead cells are simply the result of this ongoing process.",
